Philippine Stocks: East Asia, Manila Electric, Metro Pacific

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-06-02T04:47:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-02/philippine-equity-movers-manila-electric-san-miguel-corp-.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in  Manila .  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 0.9 percent to
4,324.98.  East Asia Power Resources Corp. (PWR)  , which operates
 power plants , surged 25 percent to 65 centavos, the highest
close since April 2001, after Century Properties Inc. agreed to
buy the equivalent of 93.6 percent of East Asia from a major
shareholder for 127.4 million pesos ($2.9 million).  It will hold a tender offer from June 3 to July 11 for the
other East Asia shares, according to a stock exchange filing.
Century Properties may use East Asia to list on the exchange,
the Philippine Star reported today.  Manila Electric Co. (MER)  , the largest Philippine power
retailer, climbed 7.5 percent to 268.80 pesos, the highest in
more than four months. The utility is in talks with potential
partners for its venture into power generation, a stock exchange
filing showed. The company plans to build a portfolio of up to
1,500 megawatts of power projects and invest 9 billion pesos in
equity for an initial 600 megawatts of generating capacity.  Metro Pacific Investments Corp. (MPI)  , a unit of  Hong
Kong ’s First Pacific Co., gained 2.3 percent to 3.52 pesos, the
sharpest increase since April 29. The government’s Bases
Conversion and Development Authority said it hasn’t terminated a
toll-road contract with the company’s unit. The authority and
Metro Pacific’s unit are continuing talks to “improve” the
contract’s terms, the authority said in a statement yesterday.  The authority wrote to Metro Pacific, saying it would like
to terminate a 25-year concession to operate the 94-kilometer
Subic-Clark-Tarlac Expressway, BusinessMirror reported May 22,
citing Metro Pacific Chairman Manuel Pangilinan.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
